Information and link regarding tomorrow night's Varsity football game:

All gates will open at 5:45pm
No lawn seating available
Accommodations will be made as needed
Seating is available on the home side, the south end zone and overflow on the visitors side
There is to be no reserving seats prior to the gates opening
All COVID guidelines must be followed which includes a self assessment prior to your arrival, wearing your mask and social distancing
The elementary school will not be available for restrooms
There are several hand sanitizing stations set up throughout the facility
Tailgating is NOT permitted in the parking lots
There is to be no congregating in parking lots and along the fence line prior, during and/or after the game
All tickets are $5 each
No Re-Entry
At the conclusion of the game all spectators are asked to exit the stadium immediately
Tomorrow night will surely look different, but we appreciate all the efforts that everyone has made to ensure our athletes are getting an opportunity to play.

https://youtu.be/SbzhIeA67ho

Go Trojans!

post_text:
Due to COVID restrictions, tickets to ALL athletic events will only be available through participating students at the events. This includes athletes for all events, and band and cheerleading specifically for home football games. A specific number of ticket vouchers will be given to each student participant. Those vouchers will need to be brought to the ticket booth at the sporting event so you can pay for an official ticket. Individuals on the same voucher (from the same player) must sit together as a group. There will be no tickets for sale at the gate for anyone that does not have a voucher. No passes of any sort will be accepted. A free, live stream of the football games and volleyball games will be provided through a youtube channel. No one will be permitted to stand outside the stadium to view the game. Let's allow the students to compete by following the state's mandates.

If you have any further questions, please email Mr. Hebenthal or Mr. Porter. Thank you.

Elementary Virtual Open House - Tuesday, August 18, 2020

Scheduled times:

4:30pm - 1st Grade VOH
5:00pm - 2nd Grade VOH
5:30pm - 3rd Grade VOH
6:00pm - 4th Grade VOH
6:30pm - 5th Grade VOH

Directions to participate:

1. Go to https://meet.google.com/

2. Click "Join or Start a Meeting"

3. Type in the "Nickname" for your grade level. For example: 1st Grade VOH. The host will accept you.

The grade level team will be on to introduce themselves and answer questions during the Virtual Open House.

Bring in basic school supplies the first day of school and you can slowly send in the rest later throughout the week. We don't expect the students to come with everything the first day.

This is for Centerburg Elementary! This is Mr. Thompson, the new principal. I'm excited to begin the school year with all of you. I will be mailing out a letter of introduction, new pick up procedures, Covid protocols, Open House info, etc.

Usually the class lists are posted this Friday. Unfortunately, due to Covid there has been a delay with the lists and they will not be posted until Friday, August 14th.

If you still have a Chromebook at home, please return it to the school ASAP. We need them all returned to be cleaned and updated. You will get a new one if you are doing remote learning with pickup to be announced at a later date and time.

Dear Parent/Guardian:

It is time to start getting ready for the 2020/2021 school year. In addition to the current school immunization requirements (which includes the 7th grade mandated Tdap), all incoming 7th and 12th grade students will need to show proof of receiving the meningitis vaccine.

If you would like to get your child vaccinated, below are the following locations and times to accommodate you.



Knox County Health Department, 11660 Upper Gilchrist Road Mount Vernon, Ohio 43050

*By appointment only.

*8 a.m. to noon and 1-4 p.m. and until 6 p.m. on the third Tuesday of the month.

*To schedule an appointment, please call the Knox County Health Department at (740) 399-8009.

post_text:
Class of 2027 Presidential Academic Award Winners

Centerburg Elementary is pleased to announce the winners of the 2020 Presidential Academic Award. This award is the most prestigious award given at Centerburg Elementary and serves as appropriate punctuation on what has been an outstanding academic career up to this point in a student’s life. In order to earn the award, a student must maintain a minimum grade point average of 3.5 during 4th grade and the first semester of 5th grade. The student must also perform at the 85th percentile or higher on state tests.

The following students have earned the Presidential Academic Award for 2020.

Tressie Beverly
Annamarie Clevenger
Kailee Foreman
Morgan Gaboric
Claire Hill
Carly Law
Dayna Meier
Carter Rhodebeck
Jocelyn Tabor

post_text: The Centerburg FFA Chapter would like to introduce Ms. Taylor Scowden as its 2020-2021 FFA Reporter!! She is an upcoming Senior and has been a member of the Chapter for 3 years. Taylor said " I wanted to become an FFA Officer because I wanted to become more involved with the chapter. I love to help people, and I wanted other students to know that they can come to me with anything and I will always do my best to help them. By becoming an officer, I believe that this will show people that I am always there to help." She is extremely involved in countless FFA Activities and also the Centerburg Volleyball Program. "My favorite memory so far is playing in the talent show at state convention." We look forward to your year of service to our chapter, Taylor!!

post_text:
Senior Spotlight - Ellis Grizinko

I am a quiet guy that likes to draw, watch funny videos, hang out with my family, and kick footballs. My favorite foods are chicken, yogurt, and anything sweet.

I currently live in Centerburg with my parents, Lisa and Joe Grizenko, and my older brother Nathan. My mom is currently a kindergarten teacher's aide at Centerburg Elementary School. My dad is a controls engineer in Lewis Center. My older brother, Nathan, is graduating from Ohio Northern University this year and moving on to Ohio State for grad school. I also love my grey cat Stormy.

I did marching band for 1 year in 8th grade. For the past four years I played on the football team. This year I was First Team all Conference Kicker. I have been working at the Sunbury Tim Hortons for the last two years. I love visitors so come by and see me.

After graduation I plan on attending Hocking College majoring in Fire and Emergency Services. This will give certifications for fire fighting, EMS, and paramedic. I also plan on trying out to be the kicker for the Hocking Hawlks football team.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight - Aeryn Walters

I moved down to the Centerburg area when I was 8 but did not actually go to Centerburg until my freshman year. I joined the Cross Country team where I made my first friends which ultimately introduced me to the community. Since then, I made many new friends, went to state in both cross and track with my team, went to my first football game, went to my first dance, and learned many new things about myself. Centerburg has become my home!

I live with my parents and two younger sisters. I also have 3 dogs, 4 puppies, and 6 cats.

I have run Cross Country freshman through senior year and ran Track my freshman through junior year. I am currently training for my senior track season. I am also a member of the Ohio Scholars Association and have been for two years now.

After high school I plan to study to become a Physical therapist and to also continue my athletic career and run both Cross Country and Track.

Class of 2020,

You will have the opportunity to participate in a reverse parade on Saturday May 16th from 6:00 - 6:30 in the high school parking lot. Seniors please arrive at 5:45. You will be spaced out around the parking lots - safely social distancing - while friends, family, and community members drive by to wish you well. You will not be permitted to congregate in large groups and your participation is not required. We hope this opportunity to celebrate will put a smile on your face and reinforce how proud we are of all of you!

Sincerely,

Mr. Gallwitz

Senior Spotlight - Aubrie Perry

My name is Aubrie Perry. I am in the cosmetology program at the Knox County career center. I participated in track and cross country. In my free time I enjoy hanging out with friends, playing with my dogs, spending time with my family, coloring, and watching netflix.

I am a big family person. I have three siblings, one older and two younger, Dreanna, Kelby, and Colton. My dad is a financial analyst at a company in Delaware called Greif inc. My mom is the assistant director of nursing at Living faith home health agency. My sister Dreanna graduated from centerburg last year. Kelby and Colton are still both students at Centerburg.

I ran track all four years of high school. I have participated in cross country the past three years. I was a competitive gymnast for 5 years. I am a part of a couple clubs at the career center as well.

I am undecided on what I will do after graduation but I will either take a gap year and work at a salon or attend Indiana Wesleyan University for physical therapy prerequisites.

Senior Spotlight - Jacob Frederick

My name is Jake Frederick, I went to Centerburg for three and a half years and sophomore year decided to attend the Knox County Career Center for Precision Machining. I love to work with my hands, my main passion is working on cars, motorcycles, anything with an engine. I enjoy playing guitar and learning new songs as well.

I love my family and spending time with them. I have three sisters, Jesse, Maggie, and Sara. My mom's name is Carol Frederick and my dad's name is Gary Frederick and they have helped me through so much in life and I could not ask for better parents.

I co-op at Ariel Corporation.

My future plan is to go straight into the workforce at Ariel and eventually start my own business doing small engine repair.

Senior Spotlight - Grace Mulpas

My name is Grace and I’m 18 years old. I have grown up in Centerburg and always gone to school and church here. My favorite color is lavender. I love to travel and hang out with my friends.

I live with my mom and dad. I have 2 older brothers and 1 older sister. My oldest brother is married with 4 kids, 2 boys and 2 girls. My sister is also married with 2 kids. 1 boy and she just had a baby girl about a week ago! My 2nd brother has a daughter.

I have played basketball for most of my life and I started volleyball in 7th grade. This past year I played on the varsity team for both and was a co-captain for both as well. This year I participated in FCA, Art club, and OSA.

My future plans are to attend Ashland University and major in social work.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight - Zoe Webb

I enjoy reading, shopping, and spending time with my friends. I also love succulent plants, ice cream, and the color pink!

I am the daughter of Angie and Bill Webb and I am an only child. I love spending time with my family and my dog, Bubba.

I serve as the senior class president and as the president of the Ohio Scholars Association. I am also a member of the Youth Philanthropy Initiative and concert choir at Centerburg. I participated in cheerleading at Centerburg all 4 years of high school, and I am a dancer at Infusion Dance. I am also currently earning my certification to become a yoga instructor at Yoga on High.

I plan to attend Ashland University in the fall. I am very excited to step out of my comfort zone and learn to stunt while being a flyer on the cheer squad, while I will also be a member of the dance team. I hope to double major in exercise science and nutrition, and eventually earn my doctorate of physical therapy.

Senior Spotlight - Lydia Grandstaff

I am a senior at Centerburg High School. In my free time, I like to color and hang out with friends. I am a big sweets person, and ice cream is definitely my favorite. Also, I’m a HUGE Netflix binger, so if you need a good show hook up, let me know!

I have three brothers, Jacob, Nathan, and Luke. Jacob and Nathan both graduated from Centerburg, and Luke is in the 10th grade. My parents, Brenda and Brad, both graduated from Centerburg as well. So Centerburg really is my hometown. I also have two dogs, Vise and my new puppy, Sadie!

I am involved in Centerburg’s Ohio Scholar Association (OSA) where I was head of our carnation committee. I ran cross country and played basketball all 4 years of high school. I have participated in track just these past 2 year (junior and senior year). Within my church, I volunteer with the younger kids as well as teaching the middle/high schoolers.

After graduating, I am attending Walsh University to major in Nursing.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight - Lula Burke

I find that my school hobbies and my personal hobbies—photography, sustainability, music, politics—are very much aligned. Lately, my friends and I have been doing a lot of hiking outside: I hope we can have a few last midnight Meijer trips before we all disperse.

I have a little sister, Layke, who is an incredible artist and is following my footsteps in the percussion section. My family and I live on what we call a “sanctuary farm” and have a constantly growing amount of animals.

I am Editor-in-Chief of the school newspaper, the Trojan Crier, and anchor for Prior Crier, the school broadcast. I have also been a member of the jazz band for six years and the marching band for five.

I will be attending Denison University for narrative journalism with a pre-graduate track in law. I believe it is valuable for people to have reliable, non-biased news, especially in times of chaos and nepotism. Although that sounds serious, my real plans are to keep things interesting and meet people with whom I feel connected.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight - Natalie Coffing

I am a quiet, athletic, and artistic person. Playing volleyball and creating art are two of my passions. This year I was the speaking captain of the varsity volleyball team, and I currently volunteer with the youth volleyball camps. I believe in living a minimalist life; not taking more than you need and putting God and family first. I love nature, spending as much time as I can outdoors being active.

My parents have been married for 30 years. I have two older siblings that graduated from Centerburg. I also have two nephews that I adore.

I am a member of the Centerburg Art Club. I was also on a Club Volleyball team for three years, and played school volleyball for six years. I was a band member for six years until volleyball took all my interest and time.

I am attending Columbus State Community College after graduation. I will be pursuing a career as a Paramedic and Firefighter.

post_text: Kindergarten registration is postponed until further notice. We will reschedule it after the Governor and Dr. Acton lift the restrictions on gatherings. In the meantime, the Class of 2033 can be working on learning their letters, counting objects up to 20, identifying shapes, learning to use scissors, coloring inside the lines and solving quadratic equations. We will be in touch when we are better able to get it rescheduled. Stay safe. JM

post_text:
March 30, 2020

Charter is offering free Spectrum broadband and Wi-Fi access for 60 days to households with K-12 and/or college students who do not already have a Spectrum broadband subscription at any service level up to 100 Mbps. To enroll, consumer customers should call 1-844-488-8395. Installation fees will be waived for new student households. The representatives at this number can guide consumers on qualifications and process.

The Governor announced today that schools will remain closed through May 1. All scheduled activities for the district are cancelled. We will have spring break from April 6-13 as normal. There will be no online classes during that week.

Unfortunately, because of the inability to reschedule the venue, DJ and other supports needed, the Prom this year is cancelled.

If your financial picture has changed you may qualify for free meals for school students. Please contact Autumn.Pauley@centerburgschools.org

Ms. Pound's and Mrs. Barnard's English class is reading Call of the Wild. So Wednesday they went to see the movie and afterward went to the Humane Society where they spent some time with dogs and cats who need homes. Afterward, they wrote bios for the animals and will share them with the Humane Society in hopes that their bios will help connect the pets with their new homes.

UPDATE: Due to time constraints for those wanting to take the Accuplacer and have yet to apply...

*Please note that we will be offering the Accuplacer at a later date. It will NOT be Feb 19th. The new date is March 11th @ 8:30am.

College Credit Plus students for next school year:

If you are looking to take the Accuplacer in hopes of being accepted to the CCP program, please note that we will be offering it here at Centerburg HS on February 19th @ 8:30am.

North Central State College is administering this exam for us, but you MUST COMPLETE THE FOLLOWING LIST PRIOR TO:
1) Show proof of attending a CCP informational meeting.
2) Get online and apply for North Central State College CCP program.
3) Notify the guidance office of your request to sit for the exam.

**This will be at no cost to you as long as you fulfill the items listed above.

post_text: Our 4th graders recently completed the 6 week Crunch Out Obesity program. The program is sponsored by United Way, YMCA, KCH, Health Dept., gethealthyknox.org , and all schools in Knox County. At the end of the program every 4th grader wrote a reflective essay about how the program impacted their lives. Winners were chosen from each classroom. Our winners were Parker Meyhoefer, Amie Burch, Avery Gunder and Regan Williams. To top it all off, Regan was named as the county wide winner of the essay contest ! Thanks also to Mr. Dodrill for coordinating the program and inspiring the kids to be healthy.
